<HEAD>Antarctic Cleanup Ends With Oil Still Aboard Wrecked Ship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALMER STATION, Antarctica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multimillion-dollar
international cleanup effort is concluding at the site of a wrecked
Argentine supply ship that still holds about 63,000 gallons of
diesel fuel, U.S. and Argentine officials said.
   The authorities interviewed this week said little more could be
done with the half-sunken ship, the Bahia Paraiso, before the
Antarctic winter sets in.
   ``The mission is practically completed,'' said Capt. Heberto
Rubatino, head of the Argentine navy's anti-pollution office. ``We
are sure we have checked out, cleaned up and controlled all of the
Bahia Paraiso's tanks.''
   Rubatino, in a meeting with U.S. authorities aboard an Argentine
navy cargo ship anchored near the site, said some of the Bahia
Paraiso's fuel storage tanks could not be reached safely by divers
to pump them out. He said they had been sealed.
   A U.S. navy salvage expert, William Walker, said the ship still
held about 63,000 gallons of diesel fuel. He agreed the fuel was
unreachable.
   He said the vessel had been carrying about 265,000 gallons of
diesel fuel when it ran aground Jan. 28 on shoals about two miles
from Palmer Station, a U.S. research base on the Antarctic Peninsula
about 600 miles from the tip of South America.
   The Bahia Paraiso rolled over and partially sank three days after
it ran aground. It is on its side, and part of its gashed orange
hull and its deck remain above the water line. The waters
immediately around the wreck are discolored and smell of fuel.
   The United States, Chile and Argentina sent teams and equipment
to the site. Walker said about 16,400 gallons of fuel was pumped out
of the wreck, after hundreds of thousands of gallons leaked out.
   Walker also said any effort to salvage the vessel, or to cut it
up and remove it from the site, would take three years and cost as
much as $60 million _ far more than the ship's value. Any decision
on whether to salvage the vessel would have to be made by Argentine
authorities, he said.
   Peter Wilkniss, polar programs director for the National Science
Foundation, said clean-up efforts by Argentine and U.S. experts
would conclude about March 15. He said scientists from the United
States, Argentina and Chile was being sent to Palmer Station to
study the spill's effects on the area's wildlife. The foundation
supervises all U.S. activities in Antarctica.
   He said the diesel still in the ship's tanks was expected to
continue to leak, ``maybe for as long as a year.'' Some floating
containment booms would be placed to try to control the leakage.
   ``There's little more we can do before winter sets in,'' he said.
   ``The best thing that could happen, as cruel as it sounds, is for
it (the ship) to break up and spill its guts all at once,'' he said.
This would bring contamination to a quicker end and allow the
wildlife to recuperate, he said.
   Wilkniss said, however, that experts were unable to predict
whether the ship would break up in a big storm or slowly rust
through.
   The Palmer Station area abounds with wildlife, including penguins
and seals. Scientists say they have found many dead seabirds,
including skuas and cormorants, and a few dead penguins, but are
unable to say for certain if pollution was to blame.
   Pollution experts say diesel fuel, because of its high
volatility, evaporates quickly and is less damaging to wildlife than
thicker petroleum products.
   On Feb. 26, a Peruvian research ship, the Humboldt, ran aground
in Antarctica near King George Island, 300 miles from Palmer
Station. Authorities said the Humboldt spilled a small amount of
fuel that was treated by the Chilean navy with chemical dispersants.
The ship was refloated March 6.
</TEXT>
