<HEAD>Environmentalists Urge Curbs on Tourism in Antarctica</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental group on Saturday urged the
government to protect penguins and other Antarctic wildlife by
regulating companies that take tourists to that ice-bound continent.
   ``Repeated tourist visits will cause animals to abandon their
breeding sites or increase the vulnerability of their eggs and
young to predation,'' Environmental Defense Fund attorney Bruce
Manheim said in a statement.
   The New York-based group issued a report calling on the National
Science Foundation, the State Department and the Coast Guard to
establish a licensing system to ensure no damage to Antarctica from
tour groups.
   ``Although remote and generally inhospitable, Antarctica is now
visited by thousands of tourists each year who wish to see the
continent's pristine environment before it could be despoiled,''
the report said.
   It said ``most tourists are seriously concerned about protecting
Antarctica'' but ``their visits are often localized repetitive and
frequently occur at breeding grounds for penguins, seals and other
seabirds.''
   The report said ``frequent helicopter visits by the first
tourists to Antarctica _ diplomats and dignitaries visiting McMurdo
Station _ quickly resulted in a 50 percent reduction in the
southernmost Adelie Penguin rookery at Cape Royds.''
   It said Antarctic tourism is growing and one Australian company
hopes to develop and a hard-surface runway and luxury hotel on the
continent.
   Currently, however, most of the tour companies are American and
thus the federal government could do much to limit environmental
damage, it said.
   The group urged a ban on aircraft overflights within 1,500
meters of wildlife sites, guidelines on government observation of
wildlife, management plans for wildlife sites, advance information
requirements for expeditions, and coordination of tour visits to
wildlife areas.
   It also called for a monitoring program to assess the impact of
such visits, a ban on the disposal of oil, plastics and garbage
from tour vessels and strict regulation of vessel operations in
waters off Antarctica.
   The report was released on the first anniversary of the
grounding of the Bahia Paraiso, an Argentine tour vessel that
spilled more than 180,000 gallons of oil into wildlife breeding
areas, the report said. ``A year after Antarctica's most
significant environmental disaster, we still don't have regulations
to prevent similar catastrophes,'' it said.
</TEXT>
