<TEXT>     And another.;    Soon, more than a dozen penguins were completely out of
their shells.;    For a professional egg hunter such as Hill, this was a real
pickle to be in. For only the second time in his 34 years of collecting
penguin eggs from Antarctica and flying them back to his beloved Birdland, a
tourist attraction in south-central England, Hill's precious cargo had begun
to hatch in midair.;    By the time Hill and his entourage of 101 king and
chinstrap penguins arrived in Miami, 14 of them were out of their dirty white
eggs, napping in the 96.5-degree darkness of three egg incubators.;    "I had
