<LEADPARA>  Scottie Bowman leans forward in the office chair and disappears briefly behind
a cluttered desk as he undoes the laces of his skates. It is disconcerting to
see Bowman behind that desk when one is accustomed to seeing Bob Johnson
there, chattering for hours about the most obscure, seemingly irrelevant
hockey subjects.;   Bowman provides an obscure detail of his own. The
Pittsburgh Penguins will play 23 divisional games in the first half, he says,
and 13 of them will be played at home. That tidbit is worthy of Johnson.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  INTERIM STATUS SUITS HIM FINE
PENGUINS' BOWMAN VOWS TO STAY ON JOHNSON'S COURSE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Pro Hockey  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     And after all, Bowman is sitting in Johnson's office, the coach's office,
at Civic Arena. There is a wood-paneled locker by the door bearing a nameplate
that reads "B. Johnson." There is a photo of Johnson on the wall, and on the
floor is another, of Johnson, wife Martha and the Stanley Cup.;   Three
banners were raised Saturday night to the domed ceiling of Civic Arena. The
Penguins won the Patrick Division championship in the regular season and the
playoffs. They won the Prince of Wales Conference. And they won the Cup that
sits next to Johnson in the photograph.;   Johnson is fairly beaming in that
shot. The Penguins had 13 coaches in their 23 years before he arrived, and
none managed to win the Stanley Cup.;   The team celebrated that achievement
Saturday, or tried to, before a game against the New York Rangers. A telecast
of the game was available in Colorado Springs, where Johnson is recovering
from the radiation treatments he received for two brain tumors.;   "The whole
family is in Colorado Springs and they can watch it on television," Penguins
General Manager Craig Patrick said. "They're going to have a little party and
enjoy the banner-raisings just as we will.";   Saturday was the Penguins'
third home game; these things usually are done before the opener. The Penguins
had wanted to wait until Johnson was well enough to attend the ceremony, but
that wait might be very long.;   So the flags went up Saturday night and the
diamond rings were handed out Monday. Now the Penguins try to defend their
championship with another man behind Johnson's desk, behind Johnson's bench.; 
 "My approach, as an interim coach, is to make as few changes as possible,"
said Bowman, who had been perfectly happy in his role as director of player
development. "I feel my role is to try to avoid confusion -- to try to play
the same style of hockey, try to get Mario Lemieux on the ice as much as we
can, try to play him with Paul Coffey . . . the things they did a year ago."; 
 The Penguins are fortunate to have Bowman. No coach has guided more
regular-season triumphs than Bowman's 743. None has more playoff victories
than Bowman's 114. The first of his five Stanley Cup rings is 18 years old; it
is 15 months younger than the Penguins' Jaromir Jagr.;   Bob Johnson's first
Cup ring has a skating Penguin in the center and an oval diamond forming the
white belly of the bird's tuxedo. It took a lifetime to earn, and it is
totally unfair there should be so much less time to enjoy it.;   Left wing
Kevin Stevens said, "We pray for Bob," and you had to know they were thinking
of him when the flags went up Saturday night.  </TEXT>
