<LEADPARA>  HE COACHED teams to a league-record 739 victories and five Stanley Cup
championships by ruling with an iron fist, but Scotty Bowman says he is taking
a new approach with the Pittsburgh Penguins.;   Bowman, most famous for
winning five Stanley Cup titles with the Montreal Canadiens during the 1970s,
is trying to carry on the tradition established last season by Penguins Coach
Bob Johnson, who used positive reinforcement and unwavering optimism as tools
to lead the Penguins to their first Stanley Cup championship.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BOWMAN HAS CHANGED TACTICS SINCE TAKING OVER
PENGUINS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Some information in this report was obtained from writers in other cities.;
Hockey Report  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Although he had no intention of returning to coaching when the Penguins
hired him as a director of player development before last season, Bowman has
been on the Pittsburgh bench since doctors discovered in late August that
Johnson had brain cancer, which ultimately took Johnson's life Nov. 26.;  
Bowman says life on the bench has been different for him this time around.;  
"This isn't my team, really," Bowman said as he watched the Penguins practice
at the Cow Palace for a game against the Sharks last week. "Times have
changed. The players have changed. I'm just the coach this time. I'm not the
general manager, so I'm free to spend more time with the players and get to
know them a little better.";   Bowman also said some of Johnson's personality
may have rubbed off on him.;   "I saw what he did here," Bowman said. "The
inspiration he gave these players is still with them, and I don't want to try
to break that down. I want to try to keep them upbeat and look for the
positive things.";   So far, Bowman has been well received.;   "We all feel
lucky to have been coached by a man like Bob Johnson, but I think we also feel
fortunate that there was a man like Scotty Bowman there to take over in this
situation," Penguins defenseman Paul Coffey said.; WHITNEY UPDATE: Center Ray
Whitney, the second player chosen by the Sharks in June's entry draft, is
playing for the independent San Diego Gulls of the International Hockey League
and scored six goals with three assists in his first six games.;   Although
NHL rules prohibit the Sharks from assigning Whitney to their IHL affiliate in
Kansas City because he has juniors eligibility remaining, he was able to sign
with the Gulls because they have no NHL affiliate.; DIZZY: Former Olympian
Lane MacDonald, the 1989 Hobey Baker Award winner as the best collegiate
player in the United States, has retired from hockey and plans to go into
business in San Francisco.;   MacDonald was still with Team USA for an
exhibition game against the Sharks at the Cow Palace on Nov. 17, but decided
to retire because of a recurring health problem.;   Before joining Team USA,
MacDonald had been out of hockey for two years because of trauma-induced
migraines. He said the problem returned when he took a hit during an
exhibition game against the Calgary Flames in Salt Lake City in September.;  
"I couldn't talk for about 20 minutes," MacDonald said. "I couldn't put a
sentence together. It was just a little scary.";   MacDonald scored six goals
for Team USA in the 1988 winter Olympics.; AROUND THE NHL: To get a feel for
how well Winnipeg Jets goalie Bob Essensa is playing, consider this: Essensa
has allowed only 17 goals during the nine-game unbeaten streak that the Jets
are riding even though the Jets have been outshot 328-241 in those games. . .
. Montreal Coach Pat Burns, who was promoting the use of condoms after news
broke that basketball star Magic Johnson has the virus that causes AIDS, has
decided he will no longer answer AIDS-related questions because the issue has
become a distraction for his players. "I won't discuss it anymore," Burns told
reporters after practice Friday. "Hockey is our business, and we'll discuss
hockey, not AIDS or anything else." . . . The debate over realignment has
become more heated since Winnipeg officials recently began to press for a move
back to the Norris Division, and the issue had to be tabled during a Board of
Governors meeting last week. The Jets moved from the Norris Division to the
Smythe in 1982, but insist they did so only on the condition that they be
moved back when the league added another western team. That condition was met
when the Sharks joined the league this season, but not everyone wants to
tamper with the status quo. "The whole league is being inconvenienced by the
Jets," one governor told the Canadian Press.  </TEXT>
